## 8. Side-by-side comparison table

| Dimension                          | Supportive PMO           | Controlling PMO            | Directive PMO             |
| ---------------------------------- | ------------------------ | -------------------------- | ------------------------- |
| Primary role                       | Enable                   | Govern                     | Manage                    |
| Authority level                    | Low                      | Medium                     | High                      |
| Relationship with project managers | Coach / advisor          | Supervisor / reviewer      | Direct leader             |
| Main value                         | Capability building      | Consistency and compliance | Delivery control          |
| Best context                       | Mature, autonomous teams | Standardized environments  | High-stakes projects      |
| Main risk                          | Too weak to drive change | Can feel bureaucratic      | Can reduce local autonomy |

---

## 9. Advantages and possible drawbacks

| PMO Type        | Main advantages                                     | Potential drawbacks                                     |
| --------------- | --------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Supportive**  | Flexible, collaborative, developmental              | May lack authority in weak or chaotic environments      |
| **Controlling** | Standardized, predictable, compliant                | May be perceived as rigid or bureaucratic               |
| **Directive**   | Fast decisions, strong control, high accountability | May centralize too much power and reduce team ownership |

> Important interview insight:
> **Every PMO design is a trade-off between autonomy and control.**

